<subsection xml:id="subsec-percents">
    <title>Percents</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>
            Percents are a way to express a number as a fraction of 100. 
            The word "percent" means "per hundred." For example, 50% is the same as 50 out of 100, or 50/100. 
            The symbol for percent is <m>%.</m>
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-working-out-percentage-change-of-given-quantities-in-real-life-situations">
        <title>Working Out Percentage Change of Given Quantities in Real Life Situations</title>

        <activity>
            <title>Work in Groups.</title>
            
            <p>
                Consider the following information
            </p>
            <p>
                Moraa takes five days to till a vegetable garden.
            </p>
            <p>
                Ruto takes ten days to till the garden.
            </p>
            <p>
                In your groups, discuss the following and record your findings.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What fraction of the garden can Moraa till in a day?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What fraction of the garden can Ruto till in a day?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What fraction can they till in a day if they worked together?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Share your findings with other groups.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </activity>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> \amp {\text{Key Takeaway}} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Increase or decrease in quantities can be expressed as percentages of the original quantities.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Percentage increase can be represented as;
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            Percentage increase =  (\frac{increase}{original}) \times 100 \%
                        </me>                
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Percentage decrease can be represented as;
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            Percentage decrease = (\frac{decrease}{original}) \times 100 \%
                        </me>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A box cnatains <m>25</m> pens. If five more pens are added into the box,
                    find the percentage increase in the number of pens in the box.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Percentage increase} =  \amp (\frac{\text{Number of pens added}}{\text{Initial number of pens}}) \times 100 \%</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>= \amp (\frac{5}{25}) \times 100 \% </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>= \amp 20 \% </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>

            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A basket contains <m>10</m> mangoes. Three mangoes were removed.
                    Find the percentage decrease in the number of mangoes in the basket.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Percentage decrease} = \amp (\frac{\text{Number of mangoes removed}}{\text{Initial number of mangoes}}) \times 100 \% </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>= \amp (\frac{3}{10}) \times 100 \% </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>= \amp 30 \% </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsubsection>    
</subsection>